{
    "id": "audioutil",
    "lang": "en-us",
    "name": "AudioUtil",
    "description": "Play sound effects and music: quick one-shot sounds (flat or positioned in 3D), control an attached audio player, change pitch, and mute everything.",
    "link": "/docs/uniscript/en-us/audioutil",
    "tags": [
        "uniscript",
        "audioutil",
        "audio",
        "sound",
        "music",
        "sfx"
    ],
    "previous": {
        "name": "PlayerUtil",
        "link": "/docs/uniscript/en-us/playerutil"
    },
    "next": {
        "name": "UIUtil",
        "link": "/docs/uniscript/en-us/uiutil"
    },
    "content": [
        {
            "id": "block-001",
            "tag": "h1",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "AudioUtil"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-002",
            "tag": "p",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "`AudioUtil` plays sound in your game — coin pings, footsteps, explosions, and music. There are two easy ways to make a sound: a quick **one-shot** (fire and forget) or an **attached audio player** you can start, stop, and tweak over time."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-003",
            "tag": "note",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "The sound-playing methods take an **audio asset** — a sound file you wire into a field in the editor."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-004",
            "tag": "h2",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Quick one-shot sounds"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-005",
            "tag": "p",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "One-shots are perfect for short effects. There are two kinds: **2D** (heard equally everywhere, ideal for UI clicks and music) and **3D** (comes from a position in the world, so it's louder when you're close)."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-006",
            "tag": "table",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "headers": [
                "Method",
                "What it does"
            ],
            "rows": [
                ["`Play2DAudio(asset, volume)`", "Plays a flat sound at the chosen `volume` (`0`–`1`). Great for clicks, pickups, and UI."],
                ["`Play3DAudio(asset, position, volume)`", "Plays a sound at a spot in the world — it fades with distance."],
                ["`Play3DAudio(asset, position, volume, distanceMode, minDistance, maxDistance)`", "A 3D sound with control over how it fades (see below)."]
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "block-007",
            "tag": "code",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "lines": [
                "// A UI click — same volume everywhere.",
                "AudioUtil.Play2DAudio(clickSound, 1.0);",
                "",
                "// An explosion at the player's position — fades with distance.",
                "vector3 pos = UniObjectUtil.GetWorldPosition(this);",
                "AudioUtil.Play3DAudio(explosionSound, pos, 0.8);"
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "block-008",
            "tag": "p",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "For the detailed 3D version, `distanceMode` controls how the sound fades: `0` for **logarithmic** (natural falloff) or `1` for **linear** (even fade). `minDistance` is how close you can get before it's at full volume, and `maxDistance` is where it fades to silence."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-009",
            "tag": "h2",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "An attached audio player"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-010",
            "tag": "p",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "When you need ongoing control — looping music, an engine hum you start and stop — attach an audio player to an object with `AddAudioPlayer`, then drive it:"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-011",
            "tag": "table",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "headers": [
                "Method",
                "What it does"
            ],
            "rows": [
                ["`AddAudioPlayer(this)`", "Adds an audio player to the object (set its clip in the editor)."],
                ["`Play(this)`", "Starts playing."],
                ["`Stop(this)`", "Stops and rewinds to the start."],
                ["`Pause(this)`", "Pauses, keeping the position so `Play` resumes."],
                ["`SetPitch(this, value)`", "Changes the pitch/speed — `1.0` is normal, higher is faster and squeakier."]
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "block-012",
            "tag": "code",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "lines": [
                "class EngineSound",
                "{",
                "    void OnInit()",
                "    {",
                "        AudioUtil.AddAudioPlayer(this);",
                "        AudioUtil.Play(this);",
                "    }",
                "",
                "    // Make the engine rev with speed.",
                "    void SetSpeed(float speed)",
                "    {",
                "        AudioUtil.SetPitch(this, 1.0 + speed * 0.1);",
                "    }",
                "}"
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "block-013",
            "tag": "h2",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Muting everything"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-014",
            "tag": "p",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "`SetAudioActivition` turns all game audio on or off at once — perfect for a mute button. Pass `true` for sound on, `false` to silence everything."
        },
        {
            "id": "block-015",
            "tag": "code",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "lines": [
                "// Mute all audio.",
                "AudioUtil.SetAudioActivition(false);"
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "block-016",
            "tag": "h2",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Full method reference"
        },
        {
            "id": "block-017",
            "tag": "table",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "headers": [
                "Returns",
                "Method",
                "Parameters"
            ],
            "rows": [
                ["`void`", "`AddAudioPlayer`", "`uniscript`"],
                ["`void`", "`Play2DAudio`", "`object asset, float volume`"],
                ["`void`", "`Play3DAudio`", "`object asset, vector3 position, float volume`"],
                ["`void`", "`Play3DAudio`", "`object asset, vector3 position, float volume, int distributionMode, float minDistance, float maxDistance`"],
                ["`void`", "`Play`", "`uniscript`"],
                ["`void`", "`Stop`", "`uniscript`"],
                ["`void`", "`Pause`", "`uniscript`"],
                ["`void`", "`SetAudioActivition`", "`bool enabled`"],
                ["`void`", "`SetPitch`", "`uniscript, float value`"]
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "block-018",
            "tag": "tip",
            "styles": null,
            "classes": null,
            "text": "Use `Play2DAudio` for anything that should sound the same wherever the player is (UI, music, alerts) and `Play3DAudio` for things that happen at a place in the world (footsteps, gunfire, doors). A tiny pitch variation on repeated sounds keeps them from feeling robotic."
        }
    ]
}
